  "output": "## Codebase context\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraper (SQLite + `httpx`), not a React app — there's no frontend here, so \"re-renders\" doesn't apply literally. I've mapped the requested categories onto their real Python equivalents (redundant recomputation on hot paths, blocking calls inside async code, DB round-trips) and found concrete issues in each area.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every fetched job, `diff()` issues its own `SELECT` before deciding insert/update:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nWith boards like Microsoft/Amazon (thousands of postings, `max_pages=40`), this is thousands of individual statement executions per run instead of one bulk read.\n\n**Fix — one bulk SELECT, build a dict, then batch the writes:**\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    # SQLite caps bound params (~999); chunk if large boards push past it\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in self.conn.execute(q, chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, seen_rows, touched = [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        row = job.to_row()\n        row[\"now\"] = now\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif prev_hash != row[\"content_hash\"]:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            touched.append({\"now\": now, \"key\": job.key})\n            continue\n        seen_rows.append(row)\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    cur.executemany(\n        \"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (key, source, company, external_id, title, url, location,\n             department, employment_type, posted_at, salary_range, content_hash,\n             first_seen, last_seen)\n           VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,:location,\n             :department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,:content_hash,:now,:now)\n           ON CONFLICT(key) DO UPDATE SET title=excluded.title, url=excluded.url,\n             location=excluded.location, department=excluded.department,\n             employment_type=excluded.employment_type, posted_at=excluded.posted_at,\n             salary_range=excluded.salary_range, content_hash=excluded.content_hash,\n             last_seen=excluded.last_seen\"\"\",\n        seen_rows,\n    )\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis also fixes the redundant `content_hash` computation below.\n\n## 2. Redundant recomputation — `filters.py:11-41` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` on **every job**, recompiling the same keyword list from scratch each time:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...) -> bool:\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every call\n```\n\nWith 5,000 fetched jobs and 10 keywords, that's ~50,000 wasted `re.compile()` calls per run — this is the direct analogue of an unnecessary re-render: identical work redone on every iteration of a loop that never changes its inputs.\n\n**Fix — compile once, pass compiled patterns down:**\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          locations: list[str] | None = None,\n          cutoff: datetime | None = None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `models.py:66-69` + `store.py` (`content_hash` computed twice)\n\n`Job.content_hash` is a plain `@property` (SHA-256 over 4 fields), recomputed on every access. In the current `diff()`, a *changed* job hits it twice: once in the comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and again inside `to_row()` during `_update()`. Cheap per-call, but compounds with the N+1 fix above (the batched version already fixes this by computing `to_row()` once and reusing `row[\"content_hash\"]`). If you keep `content_hash` as a property elsewhere, consider:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _content_hash_cache: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, init=False)\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._content_hash_cache is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._content_hash_cache = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode()).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._content_hash_cache\n```\n(Only worth doing if you don't apply the batched `diff()` above, since that already collapses it to one computation per job.)\n\n## 4. Blocking calls inside async pipeline — `notify.py` + `pipeline.py:44`\n\n`fetch_all()` correctly parallelizes I/O with `asyncio.gather` + a semaphore. But `dispatch()` is called synchronously from inside `async def run()`:\n\n```python\nwith Store(cfg[\"db\"]) as store:\n    new, changed = store.diff(jobs)\n    dispatch(new, changed)   # <- synchronous, blocks the event loop\n```\n\nAnd every notifier in `notify.py` uses blocking calls: `httpx.post(...)` (not `AsyncClient`) for Slack/webhook/SMS, and a blocking `smtplib.SMTP` for email — each with a 15s timeout, run **sequentially**. In the worst case (multiple notifiers configured and slow/unresponsive), this can block the event loop for 45-60+ seconds even though nothing else in the pipeline needs it to be synchronous.\n\n**Fix — run notifiers concurrently off the event loop:**\n\n```python\nimport asyncio\n\nasync def dispatch_async(new: list[Job], changed: list[Job]) -> None:\n    async def run_one(fn):\n        try:\n            await asyncio.to_thread(fn, new, changed)\n        except Exception as e:\n            print(f\"  ! notifier {fn.__name__} failed: {e}\")\n    await asyncio.gather(*(run_one(fn) for fn in NOTIFIERS))\n```\n\nand in `pipeline.py`: `await dispatch_async(new, changed)`. Low urgency today given run frequency (12h cron per your recent commit), but worth fixing before notifier count or timeout grows.\n\n## 5. Memory / resource handling — no leaks found, worth noting what's already right\n\n- `fetch_all()` (`fetchers.py:767-788`) correctly `aclose()`s the client it owns in a `finally`, even on partial failures.\n- `Store` and the CLI/agent both use it as a context manager (`with Store(...) as store`), so the sqlite connection is always closed.\n- One latent gap: `Store.__init__` (`store.py:36-41`) calls `sqlite3.connect()` then `executescript()`/`_migrate()`/`commit()` outside a `try`; if the schema migration raises, the connection is never closed. Low risk (only fires on a corrupt/locked DB), but for correctness:\n\n```python\ndef __init__(self, path: str | Path = \"jobs.db\"):\n    self.conn = sqlite3.connect(str(path))\n    self.conn.row_factory = sqlite3.Row\n    try:\n        self.conn.executescript(_SCHEMA)\n        self._migrate()\n        self.conn.commit()\n    except Exception:\n        self.conn.close()\n        raise\n```\n\n## Priority\n\n1. **Fix #1 (N+1 in `Store.diff`)** — biggest win, scales directly with board size (Microsoft/Amazon are thousands of postings).\n2. **Fix #2 (regex recompilation in `filters.py`)** — cheap fix, real per-job cost.\n3. Fix #4 (blocking notifiers) if you add more notifiers or see slow runs.\n4. Fix #3 and #5 are minor/defensive — do them opportunistically, not urgent.\n",
